After you do all the stitching, your appliquéd block will be very wrinkled.  Use a Terry cloth pressing mat and press from the wrong side. Pull on the block a little, to flatten out the background as you press with steam. If not, you’ll have wrinkles between the shapes. 
This pressing method works well for me!

I’m showing you how to miter the corners of your borders.  It’s a great way to add a border when you have stripes, plaids, or even in solids.  The miters creat a “picture frame” to show off your quilt center.  This quilt has several striped  borders, and they are all mitered.  It’s easy and fun!

Add a bit of ric rac to your quilted project:
Lay it out how you want, glue it in place with Appli-Glue, and machine top-stitch down the center of the ric rac. 
I usually add the ric rac after my project is quilted because that is easier for the quilting, depending on the size of the project.  Larger quilt tops with ric rac are harder to add and sew after, so I sew it on to the top before it is quilted.
Simple as that! 

#jillilystudio #rileyblakedesigns #confetticottons #ricrac #embellish #quiltblock #quilting

Make perfect mitered corners on your binding. I start with 2 1/4” binding strips folded in half. Place on the quilt edge with raw edges even. Stitch 1/4” from the raw edge, stopping when you are 1/4” from the next side of the quilt.  Lift your presser foot and fold the binding to the right creating a 45 degree fold at the corner.  Then fold it back to the left, on top of itself, and turn your quilt to stitch down the next side.  Your corners will be perfectly mitered when you turn the binding to the back of the quilt. Last, hand stitch the binding on the back of the quilt.
Done!

#jillilystudio #rileyblakedesigns #quilting #bindingaquilt #quiltingtips #sew #quilt #quiltsofinstagram
